# ğŸ”¥ 2ï¸âƒ£ JavaScript Type System

JavaScript is:

## ğŸ‘‰ Dynamically Typed

You donâ€™t declare types:

```js
let x = 10;
x = "hello"; // allowed
```

Type is decided at runtime.

---

## ğŸ‘‰ Weakly Typed

JS allows implicit conversions:

```js
"5" + 2   // "52"
"5" - 2   // 3
true + 1  // 2
```

This is called **Type Coercion**.

---

# ğŸ§  Type Coercion (Very Important)

## ğŸ”¹ Implicit Coercion

JS converts automatically:

```js
"5" + 2 // string
"5" - 2 // number
```

Rule:

* `+` prefers string
* `- * /` prefer number

---

## ğŸ”¹ Explicit Coercion (Safer)

```js
Number("5")
String(10)
Boolean(0)
```

Professional devs prefer explicit conversion.

---

# âš¡ == vs === (CRITICAL)

## ğŸ”¥ Always Use `===`

```js
5 == "5"  // true ğŸ˜±
5 === "5" // false âœ…
```

* `==` â†’ checks value only (with coercion)
* `===` â†’ checks value AND type

ğŸš€ Real developer rule:

> Never use `==` in production.

---

# ğŸ“Œ Pass by Value vs Pass by Reference

## ğŸª¶ Primitive (Copy)

```js
let a = 10;
let b = a;
b = 20;

console.log(a); // 10
```

---

## ğŸ“¦ Object (Reference)

```js
let obj1 = { name: "Ali" };
let obj2 = obj1;

obj2.name = "John";

console.log(obj1.name); // John ğŸ˜±
```

Both point to same memory.

---

# ğŸ’¡ Developer Tricks

## 1ï¸âƒ£ Check Real Type

```js
